        -:   23:  * \brief Base class for all 1D and 2D array, and related expressions
        -:   24:  *
        -:   25:  * An array is similar to a dense vector or matrix. While matrices are mathematical
        -:   26:  * objects with well defined linear algebra operators, an array is just a collection
        -:   27:  * of scalar values arranged in a one or two dimensional fashion. As the main consequence,
        -:   28:  * all operations applied to an array are performed coefficient wise. Furthermore,
        -:   29:  * arrays support scalar math functions of the c++ standard library (e.g., std::sin(x)), and convenient
        -:   30:  * constructors allowing to easily write generic code working for both scalar values
        -:   31:  * and arrays.
        -:   32:  *
        -:   33:  * This class is the base that is inherited by all array expression types.
        -:   34:  *
        -:   35:  * \tparam Derived is the derived type, e.g., an array or an expression type.
        -:   36:  *
        -:   37:  * This class can be extended with the help of the plugin mechanism described on the page
        -:   38:  * \ref TopicCustomizing_Plugins by defining the preprocessor symbol \c EIGEN_ARRAYBASE_PLUGIN.
